We add `divisor_closure_eq_closure`: 
Let x, y be elements of a `CancelCommMonoidWithZero`. If x * y can be written as a product of units and prime elements, then x can be written as a product of units and prime elements.

We later use `divisor_closure_eq_closure` to prove Kaplansky's criterion (which we plan to add in a future PR).

You can probably use the tactic `induction… generalizing a b`. When everything works well, that avoids to have to rewrite the statement one wishes to prove.

Can you use your own induction principle to prove 1/ that divisor_closure_eq_closure 
et 2/ your property? (in that order)
Following our conversation, I have changed the content of the PR so it now contains the minimum to prove Kaplansky's criterion (`divisor_closure_eq_closure`).
I have been told that `cases'` would be deprecated soon. The syntax of `cases` is less comfortable but one gets used to it.
I could not find the syntax which allows to name hypotheses (when one uses `cases`) so I changed it to `rcases`. Is this fine as well?

There is a notion of “divisor-closed submonoid” in the literature — see https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00233-019-10079-0 where they study the relation between closure and divisor closure.
I don't really know what it is worth, but having it may allow to state this theorem as a kind of `divisor_closure_eq_closure`.

Using the article, I added the definition of the divisor closure (`Submonoid.divisor_closure`), of a divisor-closed submonoid (`Submonoid.divisor_closed`), two results about the monoid and the trivial monoid being divisor-closed (`top_divisor_closed` and `bot_divisor_closed`). I think it looks neater now. Thank you! I also proved that `closure { r | Prime r }` is divisor-closed (`Submonoid.closure_divisor_closed`). Should I now rename `Submonoid.closure_divisor_closed` to `divisor_closure_eq_closure` and keep the old name for `Associated_closure_of_mul_mem_closure`?

I would say that `Submonoid.divisor_closure_eq_closure` is OK.
For the other one, I have no opinion.
The definition of `divisor_closed` in that paper is a bit different: “A submonoid S ⊂ H is said to be divisor-closed if every divisor a ∈ H of some element b ∈ S lies in S.” Does it work for you?
The definition of `divisor_closed` in the paper works for me. I made the corresponding changes to the PR so it only depends on this definition now.

This is a legit proof, but I had the impression that in mathlib, people tried to avoid explicit lemmas like this in benefit of induction lemmas. (Avoiding them would require to define the induction lemma for “divisor_closure”.)
I have added the induction lemma. Could you please check it?

Je suis perturbé par la 4e condition: j'aurais dit quelque chose comme : si `p x` et si `y | x`, alors `p y`. 
Par ailleurs, est-ce que `p` vaut automatiquement pour les unités ?
(En fait, dans la condition `divisorClosed`,  c'est apparemment seulement à unité près que n'importe quel diviseur d'un élément y appartient aussi…)

J'ai modifie la 4e condition comme vous l'avez suggere. 

Maintenant, etant donne qu'on suppose `one : p 1` et `div : ∀ x (_ : p x), ∀ y k (_ : x = y*k), p y`, `p` vaut automatiquement pour les unites. (Je pense que c'etait aussi le cas quand `div` etait une condition a unite pres, en utilisant le theoreme [associated_one_of_mul_eq_one](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Algebra/Associated.html#associated_one_of_mul_eq_one))

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion · left; exact isUnit_of_mul_eq_one _ _ hprod.2.symm ```

```suggestion
theorem divisor_closure_eq_closure [CancelCommMonoidWithZero α]
    (x y : α) (hxy : x * y ∈ closure { r : α | IsUnit r ∨ Prime r}) :
    x ∈ closure { r : α | IsUnit r ∨ Prime r} := by
```
and then deal with the fact that you're using both x/y and a/b as variable names

Let's use the `induction` tactic:
```suggestion
  obtain ⟨m, hm, hprod⟩ := exists_multiset_of_mem_closure hxy
  induction m using Multiset.induction generalizing x y with
  | empty =>
    apply subset_closure
    simp only [Set.mem_setOf]
    simp only [Multiset.prod_zero] at hprod
    left; exact isUnit_of_mul_eq_one _ _ hprod.symm
  | @cons c s hind =>
    simp only [Multiset.mem_cons, forall_eq_or_imp, Set.mem_setOf] at hm
    simp only [Multiset.prod_cons] at hprod
    simp only [Set.mem_setOf_eq] at hind
    obtain ⟨ha₁ | ha₂, hs⟩ := hm
```

```suggestion
      · left; exact isUnit_of_mul_eq_one_right _ _ hk
      · left; exact ha₁
```

```suggestion
      · rw [hc]; rw [hc, mul_assoc] at hprod
        refine Submonoid.mul_mem _ (subset_closure (Set.mem_def.2 ?_))
          (hind _ _ ?_ hs (mul_left_cancel₀ ha₂.ne_zero hprod))
        · right; exact ha₂
        rw [← mul_left_cancel₀ ha₂.ne_zero hprod]
        exact multiset_prod_mem _ _ (fun t ht => subset_closure (hs t ht))
```

```suggestion

```
